{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17659688","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17659688"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":1,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T23:13:35+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T23:13:35+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"20885"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"20885","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/20885"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.1,0.35,0,0.05,0.5]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"13760"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"96701"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"13760","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/13760"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"20885"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"79331"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"10763"},{"type":"tags","id":"11793"},{"type":"tags","id":"11807"},{"type":"tags","id":"12710"},{"type":"tags","id":"12795"},{"type":"tags","id":"12796"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"33154"},{"type":"contributions","id":"33155"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"96701","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/96701"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA six-month-old infant presents with cardiomegaly, hypotonia, and hepatomegaly. Laboratory investigations reveal elevated creatine kinase levels. A muscle biopsy shows excessive glycogen accumulation within lysosomes. The infant\u0027s condition has been progressively worsening since birth.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following enzyme deficiencies is most likely responsible for this clinical presentation?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Muscle phosphorylase","Acid alpha-glucosidase","Muscle phosphofructokinase","Debranching enzyme","Glucose-6-phosphatase"],"correctOptions":[1],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe clinical presentation described is consistent with Pompe disease (type II glycogenosis), which is caused by a deficiency of \u003Cstrong\u003Eacid alpha-glucosidase\u003C/strong\u003E. This lysosomal enzyme deficiency leads to glycogen accumulation within lysosomes of multiple organs. Cardiomegaly is the most prominent feature, along with hypotonia and hepatomegaly, as seen in this infant.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe incorrect options can be explained as follows:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EMuscle phosphorylase\u003C/strong\u003E deficiency causes McArdle disease (type V glycogenosis), which typically presents with exercise intolerance, muscle cramps, and myoglobinuria in older children or adults, not in infants with cardiomegaly.\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EMuscle phosphofructokinase\u003C/strong\u003E deficiency (type VII glycogenosis) is a myopathic form that presents with exercise intolerance and muscle cramps, not with the infantile cardiomyopathy described in this case.\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EDebranching enzyme\u003C/strong\u003E deficiency (type III glycogenosis) presents with hepatomegaly and hypoglycaemia similar to von Gierke disease, but does not typically cause the severe cardiomegaly seen in this infant.\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EGlucose-6-phosphatase\u003C/strong\u003E deficiency causes von Gierke disease (type I glycogenosis), which primarily presents with hepatomegaly and hypoglycaemia. While hepatomegaly is present in this case, the prominent cardiomegaly and lysosomal glycogen storage point to a different disorder.\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EPompe disease is characterized by the accumulation of glycogen in lysosomes of multiple tissues due to the inability to break down glycogen in these organelles. The infantile form is the most severe, with cardiomegaly, hypotonia, and hepatomegaly typically presenting within the first few months of life, leading to cardiorespiratory failure if untreated.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["Glycogen storage diseases result from inherited deficiencies of enzymes involved in glycogen synthesis or degradation.","Pompe disease (type II glycogenosis) is caused by acid alpha-glucosidase deficiency, resulting in glycogen accumulation in lysosomes of multiple organs, with cardiomegaly being prominent.","The infantile form of Pompe disease typically presents with cardiomegaly, hypotonia, and hepatomegaly within the first few months of life."],"references":["Kumar V, Abbas AK, Aster JC. Robbins and Cotran Pathologic Basis of Disease. 10th ed. Philadelphia: Elsevier; 2020. Chapter 5, Genetic Disorders; p. 160-162"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"79331"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"20885"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"79331","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/79331"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-04-02T17:03:27+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-04-02T17:04:14+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"13760"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"96701"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"10763","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/10763"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Genetic disorders","sy